SIMPLE: intend
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intend
<hw>In*tend"</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*t⟦ecr⟧nd")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Intended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Intending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>entenden</ets> to be attentive, F. <ets>entendre</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>intendre</ets>, <ets>intentum</ets>, and <ets>intensum</ets>, to
intend, attend, stretch out, extend; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>tendere</ets> to stretch, stretch out. See
<er>Tend</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To stretch; to extend; to distend.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By this the lungs are <qex>intended</qex> or remitted.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To strain; to make tense.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a bow is successively <qex>intended</qex> and remedied.</q>
<rj><qau>Cudworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To intensify; to strengthen.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Magnetism may be <qex>intended</qex> and remitted.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir I. Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To apply with energy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let him <qex>intend</qex> his mind, without respite, without rest,
in one direction.</q> <rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To bend or turn; to direct, as one's course or
journey.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To fix the mind on; to attend to; to take care of;
to superintend; to regard.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Having no children, she did, with singular care and tenderness,
<qex>intend</qex> the education of Philip.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul, not being able to <qex>intend</qex> two things at once,
abated of its fervency in praying.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To fix the mind upon (something to be accomplished);
to be intent upon; to mean; to design; to plan; to purpose; -- often
followed by an infinitely with <xex>to</xex>, or a dependent clause with
<xex>that</xex>; <as>as, he <ex>intends</ex> to go; he <ex>intends</ex>
that she shall remain.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>intended</qex> evil against thee.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. xxi.
11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To-morrow he <qex>intends</qex>⟦br⟧
To hunt the boar with certain of his friends.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To design mechanically or artistically; to fashion;
to mold.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Modesty was made⟦br⟧
When she was first <qex>intended</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To pretend; to counterfeit; to simulate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Intend</qex> a kind of zeal both to the prince and
Claudio.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To purpose; mean; design; plan; conceive;
contemplate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intendancy</ent>⟦br⟧
